etymologies: 1960s; earliest use found in The Washington Post. From over- + vote

definitions: An instance of casting more votes than is permissible at an election.

etymologies: mid 17th century; earliest use found in Cornelius Burges (d. 1665), Church of England clergyman and ejected minister. From over- + vote

definitions: To defeat by a majority of votes; = "outvote".
To cast more than the permissible number of votes for a post, candidate, etc., or on a ballot paper, at an election.
